Detect and remove per-cell cross-talk (also called tag-jumps)
in an OTU table using Edgar's UNCROSS2 score (Edgar 2018,
\doi{10.1101/400762}). Unlike tail-trimming approaches
(e.g. \code{metabaR::tagjumpslayer()}), the score scales the expected leak by each
OTU's \strong{total} abundance: an abundant genuine OTU is expected to leak more
reads into wells where it is absent than a rare one.

For every OTU (row) an expected per-sample cross-talk count is computed as
\code{z = f * N / n}, where \code{N} is the OTU's total abundance across the whole
object and \code{n} is the \strong{total number of samples} (Edgar's spreading model:
cross-talk leaks into all wells, mostly the zero/low ones). Each cell then
receives the UNCROSS2 score

\deqn{s = \frac{2}{1 + \exp(k \cdot x / z)}}

where \code{x} is the observed count in that cell. The score tends to \code{1} as
\code{x -> 0} (looks like cross-talk) and to \code{0} as \verb{x >> z} (genuine signal).
Cells with \code{s >= tmin} are treated as cross-talk. The default \code{tmin = 0.1}
matches Edgar's "weak" (yellow) cut-off; use \code{0.4} for "strong" only.
}
\section{Relationship to Edgar's usearch binary}{
 This function faithfully
implements the \emph{published} UNCROSS2 score (eq. 3), verified cell-for-cell
against an independent reference. It differs from the usearch v11
\code{otutab_xtalk} binary in two ways that users should know:
\itemize{
\item \strong{Rate.} \code{f} is fixed (default \code{0.01}) unless \code{f = "auto"}, whereas the
binary \emph{estimates} it de novo. Use \code{\link[=estimate_xtalk_rate_pq]{estimate_xtalk_rate_pq()}} (or
\code{f = "auto"}) for a de novo estimate.
\item \strong{Aggressiveness.} The binary's \code{-otutabout} filtering is far more
aggressive than eq. (3): empirically it zeroes essentially every count
below the per-OTU mean (\code{N_i/n}), keeping only the few "big" source
samples, and removed ~40x more cells than eq. (3) at the same rate on data.
That behaviour is undocumented and beyond the paper, so this function does
\strong{not} reproduce the binary's filtered table; it is the gentler,
paper-faithful filter.
}

UNCROSS2 is defined for \strong{integer count} tables. The usearch binary rejects
non-integer input (\verb{Invalid count}); this function will process relative
abundances but the score's interpretation no longer holds, so prefer raw
counts.
}

